365
00:21:22,720 --> 00:21:27,820
And now Persia is left to
basically defend itself.

366
00:21:28,160 --> 00:21:30,160
Okay? The Greeks cannot be counted on.

367
00:21:30,400 --> 00:21:35,180
There will be Greek rebellions against
Alexander, but they will be sporadic.

368
00:21:35,280 --> 00:21:36,740
They will not be coordinated. Okay?

369
00:21:37,720 --> 00:21:41,940
So Darius has no choice but to confront
Alexander in two massive battles.

370
00:21:42,360 --> 00:21:44,640
So the first massive battle
is in southern Turkey.

371
00:21:44,820 --> 00:21:46,460
Anatolia caught the Battle of Isis.

372
00:21:46,600 --> 00:21:48,240
Okay? In 333 BCE.

373
00:21:48,580 --> 00:21:50,600
The second battle will happen two

374
00:21:50,600 --> 00:21:54,880
years later in Guacamole in Mesopotamia.

375
00:21:55,660 --> 00:21:58,540
And both of these battles
are about the same.

376
00:21:58,540 --> 00:22:01,060
Okay? So I will explain what
happened in both battles.

377
00:22:01,200 --> 00:22:04,900
So you're going to understand
Alexander's strategy of war.

378
00:22:05,180 --> 00:22:09,000
All right. So usually in battles,

379
00:22:09,120 --> 00:22:12,280
there are three major forces.

380
00:22:12,800 --> 00:22:14,600
There's something called the left flank.

381
00:22:14,760 --> 00:22:17,660
Okay? The center flank
and the right flank.

382
00:22:17,820 --> 00:22:19,440
And both armies are like this.

383
00:22:19,620 --> 00:22:20,880
Now, in both battles,

384
00:22:21,100 --> 00:22:25,900
the Persians were heavily
outnumbered the Greeks,

385
00:22:26,040 --> 00:22:29,300
two to one. Okay? So it's
a massive difference.

386
00:22:30,360 --> 00:22:34,520
And the cavalry is usually on the sides.

387
00:22:35,120 --> 00:22:36,940
Now, there are some certain differences.

388
00:22:37,300 --> 00:22:42,040
Okay? The first difference is the
Persians have one leader, Darius.

389
00:22:42,460 --> 00:22:46,440
And he's in the center being protected
