390
00:22:46,520 --> 00:22:49,400
The Immortals are the best
troops of the Persians.

391
00:22:49,480 --> 00:22:53,780
Okay? The Macedonians have two leaders.

392
00:22:53,780 --> 00:22:57,780
Parmonion and Alexander.

393
00:22:59,160 --> 00:23:00,940
Alexander is in charge of the cavalry.

394
00:23:01,180 --> 00:23:04,620
Parmonion is in charge of the infantry.

395
00:23:05,200 --> 00:23:06,760
What we call the phalanx.

396
00:23:06,960 --> 00:23:09,340
And in both battles,
the same thing happens.

397
00:23:09,500 --> 00:23:11,660
Which is, on the left side,

398
00:23:11,920 --> 00:23:15,520
Darius commits most of his
forces against Parmonion.

399
00:23:15,740 --> 00:23:20,140
Okay? So Parmonion is being
overwhelmed by superior numbers.

400
00:23:20,580 --> 00:23:23,760
But here, the discipline is different.

401
00:23:23,760 --> 00:23:26,160
The discipline of Parmonion
is just incredible.

402
00:23:26,360 --> 00:23:29,380
Because even though they're being
overwhelmed, okay, they're being outnumbered,

403
00:23:29,380 --> 00:23:32,460
and they're about to be outrun,
they hold their ground.

404
00:23:33,020 --> 00:23:36,220
Okay? And then, in the
right, in the center,

405
00:23:36,480 --> 00:23:40,360
there's so much conflict that eventually
what happens is there's a small gap

406
00:23:40,360 --> 00:23:43,860
that allows Alexander to rush to Darius.

407
00:23:44,120 --> 00:23:47,640
Okay? Remember, Darius is being
protected heavily because he's the king.

408
00:23:47,800 --> 00:23:51,160
Right? And at this point,

409
00:23:52,580 --> 00:23:57,580
Alexander and his forces are
overwhelming the cavalry of Darius.

410
00:23:58,020 --> 00:23:59,940
And they're about to close up.

411
00:24:00,020 --> 00:24:01,260
They're getting close to Darius.

412
00:24:01,440 --> 00:24:06,140
And at this point, what Darius does, and this
is something you can never do in a battle.

413
00:24:06,340 --> 00:24:09,520
What does Darius do now? And
he does this in both battles.

414
00:24:09,700 --> 00:24:11,940
Isis and Coromala.

415
00:24:12,160 --> 00:24:15,660
What does he do now? He sees
Alexander closing in, right?

416
00:24:15,880 --> 00:24:18,360
But his left flank is about
to overwhelm Parmonion.

417
00:24:18,560 --> 00:24:20,120
What does Darius do now?

418
00:24:20,120 --> 00:24:26,040
In both battles? He runs away.

419
00:24:26,440 --> 00:24:28,400
He runs away. And when he does that,

420
00:24:28,960 --> 00:24:31,880
Alexander is now free to go back

421
00:24:31,880 --> 00:24:35,780
and rescue Parmonion, and
then the Persians flee.

422
00:24:36,020 --> 00:24:39,200
Okay? Does that make sense? All right.

423
00:24:39,240 --> 00:24:41,860
So this is what happens in both
battles, Isis and Coromala.

424
00:24:43,760 --> 00:24:46,780
So now that you have the basic
overview of both battles,

425
00:24:46,980 --> 00:24:50,100
let's analyze this to ask you,

426
00:24:50,100 --> 00:24:53,140
let's ask ourselves, how great
a commander is Alexander?

427
00:24:53,520 --> 00:24:57,580
Okay? And I want to make you, again, make the
argument that he's actually not a great strategist.

428
00:24:58,060 --> 00:24:59,500
Okay? He's a great soldier.

429
00:25:00,080 --> 00:25:03,700
He's very brave. But he's
not a great strategist.

430
00:25:03,740 --> 00:25:06,700
Not like his father. Okay? The
first thing I will say is this.

431
00:25:07,540 --> 00:25:11,800
When military historians look at
battles, they look at the wrong things.

432
00:25:12,020 --> 00:25:15,660
Right? So they're usually
looking at manpower,

433
00:25:15,940 --> 00:25:17,240
technology,

434
00:25:17,680 --> 00:25:20,020
and resources.

435
00:25:20,040 --> 00:25:23,500
Okay? What we'll call wealth. Right?

436
00:25:23,640 --> 00:25:26,760
And if we look at battles
from this lens, right?

437
00:25:27,000 --> 00:25:28,320
Manpower, technology,

438
00:25:28,720 --> 00:25:30,240
and resources, wealth, then

439
00:25:30,240 --> 00:25:34,840
we can argue the Persians were
heavily favored in this battle,

440
00:25:34,960 --> 00:25:37,200
in this war. Right? We can say that.

441
00:25:38,140 --> 00:25:42,820
But I think this is the wrong
way to look at military strategy.

442
00:25:43,160 --> 00:25:46,700
I think if you really want to
understand who's a favorite

443
00:25:46,700 --> 00:25:49,300
and who's the underdog, you have
to look at three different things.

444
00:25:49,300 --> 00:25:51,980
These three different things are cohesion.

445
00:25:52,700 --> 00:25:55,440
The idea of cohesion is unity.

446
00:25:56,060 --> 00:26:00,840
Right? Are these soldiers
loyal to each other?

447
00:26:00,900 --> 00:26:03,120
Are they friends with each other? Okay?

448
00:26:03,600 --> 00:26:05,160
Second thing you want to
look at is discipline.

449
00:26:07,460 --> 00:26:09,940
How well trained are these troops?

450
00:26:10,540 --> 00:26:13,460
Okay? The third thing you want to
look at is the idea of devotion.

451
00:26:15,200 --> 00:26:19,280
Devotion just means how
loyal are they to the enemy.

452
00:26:19,280 --> 00:26:23,460
How loyal are they to their leaders? How
much purpose do they have in the battle?

453
00:26:24,020 --> 00:26:28,140
Okay? Does that make sense? And
what I want to show you today is,

454
00:26:28,240 --> 00:26:29,820
look at these three things.

455
00:26:30,020 --> 00:26:35,060
They give you a much better
overview or analysis of

456
00:26:35,060 --> 00:26:37,220
who the better military is. Okay?

457
00:26:37,880 --> 00:26:39,720
So, if you just look at
manpower, technology,

458
00:26:40,080 --> 00:26:43,780
and resources, then clearly the
Persians are the heavy favorites.

459
00:26:44,080 --> 00:26:47,560
Right? But if you change
your frame of reference,

460
00:26:47,840 --> 00:26:50,140
and you will look at who's the most powerful,
who has the most cohesion, discipline,

461
00:26:50,520 --> 00:26:51,960
and devotion,

462
00:26:52,500 --> 00:26:54,240
then the Macedonians are far superior.

463
00:26:54,660 --> 00:26:58,360
Right? Because look, cohesion
means they have a culture.

464
00:26:58,560 --> 00:27:00,380
They have a similar culture.
Right? They're all Greeks.

465
00:27:00,840 --> 00:27:04,560
Whereas, the Persians are
a multicultural empire.

466
00:27:04,960 --> 00:27:08,020
They don't speak the same
language, which means that

467
00:27:08,020 --> 00:27:12,820
all these different units that Darius has,
they're basically fighting by themselves.

468
00:27:14,100 --> 00:27:15,580
So, they are not coordinated. Okay?

469
00:27:16,200 --> 00:27:18,060
Does that make sense?
That's the first thing.

470
00:27:18,060 --> 00:27:19,500
Second thing is the idea of discipline.

471
00:27:20,540 --> 00:27:25,360
If you're an empire, the problem with
an empire is your soldiers don't fight

472
00:27:25,360 --> 00:27:26,760
that many battles. Right?

473
00:27:26,940 --> 00:27:28,860
Because you're an empire. No
one's going to challenge you.

474
00:27:29,200 --> 00:27:31,660
So, these soldiers, even though

475
00:27:31,660 --> 00:27:35,540
they have these very expensive armor

476
00:27:35,540 --> 00:27:38,600
and horses, they weren't disciplined.

477
00:27:38,800 --> 00:27:40,860
They didn't have experience in battle.

478
00:27:42,060 --> 00:27:44,700
Whereas, Alexander's army
is Philip's army, and

479
00:27:44,700 --> 00:27:50,180
for the past 30 years, all they did was
fight battle after battle against the Greeks.

480
00:27:50,380 --> 00:27:52,200
Okay? So, in terms of discipline,

481
00:27:52,560 --> 00:27:54,280
the Greeks are far superior.

482
00:27:54,560 --> 00:27:59,400
And then you look at
devotion. Darius is king.

483
00:27:59,680 --> 00:28:00,880
Why are people loyal to him?

